## How many wards sang new hymns each week?

This plot shows what percentage of wards sing new hymns each week. For context, includes all the data since June 2nd when the first batch came out so we can see how the roll-out of the second batch compares to that of the first batch. I've color coded it by batch: green is for the first batch, red/pink is for the second, and blue is for both combined. This division is only relevant since September 15th when the second batch came out so prior to then, only the blue lines are used. In all cases, a lighter color indicates wards that sang exactly one new hymn while a darker color is for wards that since two or more in a single meeting.




::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-5-1.png){width=768}
:::
:::


With the [first batch](/posts/new_hymns_batch1) of hymns, the reception was very warm. Pretty consistently over the 15 weeks after the first batch of hymns was released, we saw about 30% of wards singing at least one of the new ones, with a small percentage singing two or more. 

So far, the second batch is represented in this plot with just a few line segments. The green ones represent the number of wards singing hymns from the first batch (#1001--1009), with the lighter color for just one and the darker color for two in a meeting. The red/pink dots represent the second batch of hymns. In the first week after the release of the second batch, relatively few wards (around 7%) sang any of them. Meanwhile, the first batch continued as normal. This is about a quarter as many wards as what we saw with the first batch. So, overall, a very lukewarm reception. 

However, the following Sunday, September 22nd, we saw a big jump. About 20% of wards sang from the second batch, which is about three times as much as the previous Sunday. This is represented by the pink and red lines going up in the plot. Interestingly, this integration of the second batch seems to come at the expense of the first batch. The fact that both green lines---which represent the first batch---go down, means that wards are singing the latest hymns *instead of* the first batch. In fact, since their initial release in June, September 22nd was the week that saw the fewest wards singing from the first batch. 

However! Look at the blue lines. Those represent the number of wards singing new hymns total, across both batches. They actually go up. To accompany that, the gray line, which represents the number of wards that sang none of the new hymns, goes down. This basically means that more wards sang new hymns on September 22nd---about 40%---than any other week so far. So, while the second batch seems to have taken a chunk out of the first batch's apple, it didn't do so completely. In fact, several wards sang hymns from both batches. 

Overall, fewer wards sang from the second batch than even the first batch's worst week. But, it shows that more wards are singing new hymns, which is pretty awesome if you ask me. 



